node.text: Short film by @taylorglenn | We all know people whose dedication to a passion or purpose inspires us deeply. Gannett Horn's (@surfasaur) focus on his sport and love for its community embodies the best in each of us. This short film is a testament to Gannett and those who motivate us to work harder at the things we love. #riversurfing Production by @apresvisuals

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / As I travel through Western Australia, many like-minded travelers and I are seeking out desert adventures. Here in Karijini National Park, it is mesmerizing to explore these gorges as this is some of the oldest rock known on the continent, where its evolution began over 2500 million (2.5 billion) years ago.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on August 12, 2021. May be an image of nature and mountain.

node.text: Photo by @andy_best / I’ve been living a nomadic lifestyle for over a decade. Traveling for work, living on the road, pushing myself to refine my craft over and over. However, the biggest reward has been in these last two extremely difficult years traveling full time with the whole family. With COVID-19, work evaporated and we even had our second baby girl out here. It’s been a challenge, but to see their faces light up as I show them what a beautiful world we live in makes it all worth it.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on August 11, 2021. May be an image of nature and mountain.

node.text: Photo by @tarakerzhner / A photograph I took before abandoning a climbing trip due to the 2021 Cedar Creek Fire in the Okanogan-Wenatchee National Forest. I was at the Washington Pass lookout. The fire was just behind the mountain range you can see in the photo. There was a massive plume of smoke that grew in the 48 hours we were there. We had arrived to climb Liberty Bell and watched the fire escalate dramatically before they closed the road. From the day we arrived until the morning we left (the morning after I took this photo), the fire had grown substantially, and visibility/air quality was so poor that we couldn't even see the mountain range anymore. Our relationships to the mountains are forever changing alongside the worsening impacts of climate change.

node.text: Photo by Irene Yee @ladylockoff // No matter how many photos you see of a place, photographing it yourself is an entirely different experience. In June I visited Smith Rock State Park for the first time with an open mind and an arsenal of notes, but ultimately I let the light guide me. At 4:30 a.m. Genevive Walker (pictured here), Erica Moncada, and I headed out to capture the first light on the walls. Nothing I had seen previously could have prepared me for the stunning views as the sun rose overhead and three women of color worked together to create smiles, community, and beautiful images. // Every adventure begins with two simple words: Let’s go. Find the perfect @hydroflask for you and make every adventure more awesome.

node.text: Video by @guillermocerveraphoto / After winning 28 world windsurfing titles, twins Daida and Iballa Ruano (together @morenotwins) are synonymous with success, dedication and passion for the waves, the wind and everything that smells of the sea. During the past two decades the sisters have dominated, with undeniable authority, the professional windsurfing circuit, becoming an example for new generations of athletes and being clear references in the fight for gender equality in sport. #lanzarote

node.text: Photo by @michaelclarkphoto / Falling from the sky. The Red Bull Air Force skydiving during their 2021 training camp in Los Alamos, California. Working with this team is like working with Superman and Superwoman. Imagine skydiving or wingsuit BASE jumping every other day of your life. To this team nothing is really impossible. For this image the camera was mounted on Andy Farrington's helmet and set to shoot four frames per second as he jumped out of the plane. Always a blast to collaborate with this crew. #skydiving #california

node.text: Photo by @andy_best / Getting reflections like these requires an early start. I remember waking up in a dark musty cabin full of snoring adventurers, all but one other. I looked across the dimly lit cabin, the smell of a smoldering fire lingering in the air, and saw a shadowy figure rummaging through fishing gear. The clinks and clanks of fishing tackle were muffled by the shadow’s crinkling puffy jacket. The ripple of his zippers let me know he was almost ready. A cold rush of air hit us in the face as we stepped out into the dew-filled meadow. The mountains were still shrouded in blue light, the sun was coming and we had to hurry. All smiles, my buddy and I disappeared into the silent pines. It wasn’t long before we reached this gorgeous lake and complete nirvana. We did ourselves a favor and just stood there, morning birds chirping, a slight breeze crawling across the lake. This is why we wake early. This is where we belong.
